A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has now been relying on a provisional, amended text for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "broken his word" and "stepping the right with his feet".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the President, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy, while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned their backs on the idea that they were not able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 members, alternate members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles have mostly been adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Pasty" is the response of the liberals, who see it as propaganda.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have an eye on Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to the Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, because "the persons who are called for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
One can see here the first signs of a theocracy".
Liberal fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "in relation to Article 220 there may be a ambiguity, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as demanded by the associations for the defence of human rights.
The latter also share their concerns about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The fact of the blasphemy is being maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no longer refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on TV last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Bow to the Sacred Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding ceremony, walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the seastorm and fishing.
Right here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers follow the path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes there, which then come true.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at an altitude of 450 metres above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins by their own power.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited during only one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Quran manuscripts or Dead Sea Scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the former visitors and bath attendants.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are rejected in principle.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is a monument to children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and of the countries in which they died are ringing.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city was the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is said to be a hold that touches the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre today.
Bookmarks for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
You prefer to take the money in the journey in no Euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway and in Haifa the only subway line of the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which includes a transfer for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays in Israel.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, sea products, fish without scales and food, which contain both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made from pureed beans and peas (Falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-fed cats, who scatter comfortably and undisturbed through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, representing an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, prior to the visa waiver on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money on language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families that remain in their home country.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants wishing to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
It is not only language tests, but also tests that have to be put into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The total number of examination places will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to launch the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Before the law came into force, however, civil rights activists in the press asked the following question several times: What is the point?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring for both the Russians and the guest workers?
In particular, the migration authority spokesman said, the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected against their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers by 90%.
Problems arise for migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his kind months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country you are promised the one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, you will receive their passports and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Central Employment Migration Office of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that not only do they not know the language of the target country, but they can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It is difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access for unauthorized persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
Moreover, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely fake and we are not registered, and this then leads to cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says Tajike Umed Hushkadamov to journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the costs of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some falsified certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The falsified papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to spare himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that certificates cannot be bought simply, is something that both officials and civil rights activists agree on.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Ministry of the Interior ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten the arms law for private arms owners.
The authorities are reacting to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the amok run of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and increase the age of possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be presented to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various arms associations - ask the authorities to refrain from "sensibly tightening up".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasiliy Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the Ministry of the Interior statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were committed over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, in Moscow, you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website accepting weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel are illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from the police's armory and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps often exploded.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore are squandering their weapons under their hands on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to the investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and the judicial authorities.
Half of all weapons in the black market were there through the "debt of those responsible who have to do with weapons in their work," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% are due to thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store who does not want to be named assures us that no one has been buying weapons found in illegal excavations for a long time, since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supplies in an armory.
An ensign buys a weapon, for example a TT-type gun.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and therefore, if they fail to comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically purchase checks from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers find each other most often through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested to come to the station "Begovaja", where a person would wait for me, who would bring me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
The price of the gun I only got there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and meet with a code like "from Ivan Ivanovich, who lets tell that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm actually coming to some rings about an acquaintance I trust.
He also gives me the rings because he knows I don't rat him out.
