Birth in Space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board are searching for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question is how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"In other words, Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Starberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, the surface of Venus has a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first dealt with the question of reproduction in space in terms of flora.
Experiments with plants were already carried out half a century before.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to investigate the impact of weightlessness on embryo development.
It develops a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a hold; it must be able to stand on its feet and begin to move," explains the laboratory director of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without solid ground, the chicks wildly overturned.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they just died.
"We let chicks hatch twice and then set the whole thing up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes to the failed experiment with chicks in space.
The last hatching cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be present on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"It was just with the biosatellites, but again it was only a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sykhev.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
In contrast to animals, man could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
Such experiments are not carried out from ethical considerations.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
Tereshkova had the greatest risk.
The most valuable thing human beings have is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after that flight?
"After all, no one answered this question," says Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andriyan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988 the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Still, there's a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, the hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must seek new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydro laboratory in the cosmonaut preparation centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults feel that water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment, but infants feel that water is a natural element.
It's like little Ichtyanders testifying that life on the land got out of the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother's belly in amniotic fluid for about 9 months and that it can easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth until the first swim only two weeks pass.
"That's too little time to forget something," says baby swim instructor Marina Aksenova.
While weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman cannot escape gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles are rapidly receding and thus the ability to squeeze out the child decreases.
All right, let's get around this with birth-inducing aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the gravity, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a strain suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply miss what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," predicts Igor Pestov, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth's inhabitants set out in their spaceships to become a distant planet that will be home to their descendants born in space.
NKÚ Chief: Control of the black system fails due to political fault
The Czech Republic has good supervisory authorities and adequate laws in connection with public contracts, but is lagging behind in their application.
In a conversation for Aktuálně.cz, the Vice President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvy
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cites Prime Minister Petr Nečas' attitude to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is to check compliance with the law, is hindering its activity," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries concerning public contracts were compared.
What exactly was that about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of the European legislative body laying down how public contracts are to be handled, and that is what national legislation is building on, and finally, there is the real practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the test has not yet been completed, we have been able to see very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "strict and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to lay down new and more precise rules over and over again, and it is also necessary to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What does this project give you?
Such joint control could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect laws and reduce and adjust thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Cost-effectiveness means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this objective.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paperwork", and those who seek gaps in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
You are talking about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is similar in structure to ours and also has a college which is only slightly different. In principle, however, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also to a certain extent comparable, although Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these accounting offices in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The Federal Republic of Germany is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are administered by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the regional accounting courts there.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without concrete information. Nevertheless, Germany is often described as a role model in some respects, but one certainly cannot say that Germany is better in all things.
Is that because the examiners are better there?
This is certainly not the case, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also face problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, how important was the amendment of the Procurement Act for your authority, do you already feel any effects?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our tests.
Since our controls are carried out retrospectively, we have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we have had an impact rather in the preparatory phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "recognition of risks of inefficiency" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts examined and analysed - here, the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
