Simon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world taking place in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to jump at.
With our band The Tap Tap, we rather make fun of ourselves and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide charity event that we've been planning for two years.
For this purpose, we want to exploit the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is forecast to end at 11:10 a.m. on December 21st.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place in Prague, Brno and Ostrava at the same time from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time that the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who gave you this idea?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we not only want to gather sufficient positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state in which we are once handing over this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key rings against the end of the world, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world entitled "Weltuntergang gefalls aus".
The anthem on YouTube is already very popular today. Will it also be performed at the benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, provided that everything works and the end of the world doesn't take place...
The hymn is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together on a direct line from Czech television.
The lyrics of the hymn are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is due to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
Students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly looked after by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we then move in with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
Which criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
You can find everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and for this concert we also prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA then - would also like to combine this with appearances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage compartment. We also have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked so far without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
Opposite Prague Moscow is absolutely not accessible for disabled people. It is still unusual there, if someone is in a wheelchair alone in the city center.
It is not even a matter of course that a wheelchair user is allowed in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're still stuck in...
It should be noted, however, that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Public respect and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music association together with a colleague.
Well, and with time, as our moderator, L’a Angelovič, tends to say, it’s a little out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you cannot see it outwardly, your performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the very beginning, I felt the potential that things could be dealt with differently.
In show business, one often copies the other today.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a longer period of time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that tap tap is one of them.
Of course, the first impression the viewer usually has is compassion; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life if they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, this is not just progress for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you can't compromise on many things and you have to demand a certain discipline.
However, I believe that this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find out that they have to test twice a week, complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the enthusiasm of many quickly fades out.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only a single one: La Angelovič.
We're an open group, people coming and going, you can't stop that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
