These draft laws will then be adopted in the Bundestag.
All violence then does not originate from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim it, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, the liberal democracies are rapidly coming into a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompeius: "The state has long been in decline, and the offices have been filled with violence.
Against bribes, by illegal concealment of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption was rampant, and the people went to the election with votes already bought" ... "People with character did not apply for offices, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "One really began to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a sole rule, and that a strong man had to be elected" ... Appian thought of Pompeius, but the strong man was finally Caesar, who permanently replaced democracy with the sole rule.
As it turns out, today's society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one's own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is not in a position to recognise and enforce the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, today as it was then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not trying to achieve deeper reforms in the least.
We must therefore seek the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalisation of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's state of affairs, the demise of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already emerging.
