The film Argo: When it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, who had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to release the hostages made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages led to a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The Iran debacle contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get the refugees out of Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity with an extravagant story - they traveled disguised with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the exfiltration expert, Tony Mendez, also required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar play such as the movie Ocean's Eleven.
Thus, the levels of mood alternate in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no big differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits at the meeting table, on the official hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime novel No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that the previous films of this director removed from the standard Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet it conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck with his team also in fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping with reality - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some of its pull. It is a film that you can follow with some interest while gouting the design and the retro style reminiscent of a 70th-year-old thriller.
However, he hardly arouses enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient secret services are, it is sufficient.
Guidelines for the inflating of balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which launches an annual survey on the most absurd bank fees, has decided this year to organise the competition "Most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"This is what the EU's recent plan to introduce a 40% quota of women in the management of large European companies brought us to this idea," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, to the Právo newspaper.
Among the nominated absurdities, for example, is the European Court of Justice's ruling on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women had an advantage in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place until the end of February 2013", informed Nacher.
Among the controversial EU regulations is the mandatory incorporation of bioethanol into fuels, which are subsequently harmful to nature, the prohibition of reliable mercury thermometers, because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs much more expensive this year.
Criticism in the past also resulted in the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby from trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more Member States (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks with veto threats).
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest class of trade in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have a "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it only harmonises the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the resistance of some countries with the indication that the previous directives would lead to a waste of food.
A candidate for victory in this survey may be the EU Regulation of last year, which, according to balloons, must be indicated when selling that children under the age of eight are not allowed to inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU relied on an American study, which according to balloons is the leading cause of child suffocation.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fair toads.
Curious ideas also exist at home
A directive that affects European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone who has an official role in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue to Greece and must say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) instead.
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated not only the above-mentioned absurdities but also the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a member country.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that could be found on the day of our accession to the EU in the territory of the Czech Republic.
For example, the Czech Republic exceeded the fixed volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The organisers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of providing funding for applications for funding.
These ideas, of course, did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we have no sea.
We will apply to the EU for reimbursement," said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
He argued that the grain harvest was very high and that the state stocks were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention buying-in.
Since the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
Finally, the European Commission approached the Czech Republic to organise a call for tenders for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development under the direction of Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU) offered the municipalities support for applications for funding, in particular for the creation of funding applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations are easily becoming the target of criticism in the Member States, some experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and thus to ensure the effectiveness and development of the entire European Union deserve more recognition.
In the opinion of these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects which have nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced by individual Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
Emotions in this country also evoke the fact that the Czech Republic, like other Member States in Brussels, has to fight for the right to use specific names of traditional products and does not always win this battle.
After a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvar
The term rum may only be used for products made of sugar cane distillate, not for products made of sugar beet.
The official list of products registered in the EU now includes Carlsbader Zwieback, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, as well as the Saazer hops in the company of world-famous cheeses Feta and Gorgonzola, Lübecker Marzipan or Parma ham.
