And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says, "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of those old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town near the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000 inhabitants community has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as pretty pinsy reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become master of statistics: a library must come here!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, master of the bold bar charts and producer of funny, even cynical buildings, took the matter with usual serenity and appeared for the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in the face.
And while the jury was still staggering around and twitching with the armpits, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite souvenirs to a pyramid in size and finished his actionistly supported speech with the words: "Dear Town Municipality!"
So this is him, my proposal for the Buchenberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is filled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Büchenberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small town retorte, which up to now had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Bücheldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading open up during the walking climb of topography.
The completely glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights clearly speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and soccer playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the bookshelfs stand along the façade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The inside of the Büchenberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes balustrade, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even ingrained architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work here with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, on request of the standard.
And so one day we found a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years, a millimetre-thin plastic fleece has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a root pad.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimetres thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit of new cars and a bit of sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meter long hiking tour, the Literaturcafé not only offers a fantastic view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
