It is heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Büchenberg is under a glass lintel, the sun shines only briefly inside, even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand across the glass facade, serve as a shade and capture a large part of the solar radiation.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest are done fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial sceptic from the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully equipped - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has been developed.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
Thus MVRDV has succeeded in the supreme discipline, which is called in the Fachjargon Identity Foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained from voting on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert in US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had first signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that has been managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
What is more, Europeans do not have a coherent and consistent policy.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still takin' their role, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests had an impact on the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, against the head in the Arab countries.
It definitely does matter.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to this either, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Did Germany damage its relations with the United States by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
After all, it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly advocated a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that under Obama, the government may have a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still find leadership difficult?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to a variety of neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European politics is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum right now, who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they are uncomfortable and make them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America work together on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
