Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
While Mexico's future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, is preparing to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyses the challenges and mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is an ever-congested city, but on Monday a steel ring was built that blocks off several important transport routes to the capital and creates chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will be given the presidency and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, but the country is under the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before he went on equal terms with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, extensive part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the holiday resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Labels with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, the PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has great expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejected the opposition's accusations that the new president lacked substance.
He was a very direct man, very dedicated and had great plans for the country.
He was an outstanding statesman, but above all he was also someone who could listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway overpasses and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was engaged to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the last two years alone on a spot in Brachland near a large landfill.
During Governor Pena Nieto's term of office, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of women's murders during his term of office.
But in the worst case, his government had closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the rigor had already begun.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is placed next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But it was precisely this, according to the family, that had been denied her until now.
The authorities treated me like I was a chatterer, troublemaker, troublemaker.
They want their judgment to be accepted and their mouths shut.
"But this is not possible if there were so many formal errors and omissions," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential tie on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes in the last six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term of office.
"I hope as president he is the way he was governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is precisely what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
The D.A. claims that Bradley Manning didn't complain about mistreatment
The Procuratorate contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the charge on the grounds of harsh detention conditions
The US Army's Private is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The Procuratorate tried on Friday to find out that the army-free Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - failed several occasions to complain about the mistreatment he allegedly suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents relating to weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention period in Quantico, Virginia did not show any complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein went through the forms with Manning, which officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had been detained from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased prison conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional".
The forms, according to Fein, did not contain any complaints about mistreatment, although the officers had interviewed Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) "No problems," and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to "prevention of injuries".
The military declared that it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the risk of suicide - to its protection and to the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that he had considered suicide in Kuwait, and had become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what was going on with him or in the outside world was a burden.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said that he had tried to keep moving, because it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to the treatment of Manning.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Military Prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that during this census he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket.
During the interview on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning testified that the previous night he was forced to sleep naked. He had previously tried to show an officer that he was not a threat to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his detention levels should he be convicted at his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the terms of the detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all prisoners under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegal publication of intelligence information on the Internet, the transmission of national defence information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he is threatened with life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to accuse the emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when perplexity spread within me.
Signs refer to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I was standing there for a few seconds, unsure which one I should go to.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later, I chose Mexican-American.
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue Mexico's war on drug cartels, even though he did not give any details about it.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country's leadership under armed rifles to leave more than half of their territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official has only mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints - in the Mexican press and among the elites of the country - about how the Americans press the sovereignty of their neighbouring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the war path.
And yet Mexico’s greatest challenge lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparents part - was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now have lived the American dream, attended good schools and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of humiliating defeat and look down upon us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our gang to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, born in Guadalajara and legally immigrating to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexicans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent them.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they do not belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We are supposed to tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and how pressure is put on political leaders to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure that this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge about how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such a hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual blames, countless buildings were laid in rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed - and for the first time rockets from Gaza struck near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem to be trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, the weeks of fighting have strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though his group itself suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are imprisoned in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not yet succeeded in destroying Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders could conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a re-emerging regional power once regarded as Israel's closest Muslim ally, has taken hold of the Hamas party - just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Exulting Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could stand before the fall of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And especially the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - the by far most populous and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region in a lasting way.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is infatuated with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor who cannot even be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
Militaryly, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proved its worth and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep calmly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position. Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, not least thanks to the blocking facilities that have flowed into the West Bank and thus into the bulk of a possible Palestinian state, which, however, continue to protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared contrary to international law.
Netanyahu stands well there. His Likud party joined forces with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these deceitful Palestinians coddle and give them a state of their own?
If they were actually in control of the West Bank, would they not fire rockets just like their comrades in the Gaza Strip?
No, it's better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could put them in the balance.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and other countries, have little for Israel, they will first concentrate on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel's defence budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Mursi joined forces with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolise the beginning of a new era.
Israelis, too, should think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratisation, Palestinians are still being deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in Gaza will take its diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is that represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world and by this newspaper: two states where Israel is leaving for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop the supply of weapons to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchanges and a common Jerusalem.
External Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama must also play his part in encouraging Israel to negotiate.
During his first term in office, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the white house, it seems as if he is also averse to participation.
But that is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a major interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws for uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, there is the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font.
Australia is thus introducing the world's strictest regulations on tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
In doing so, the government assumes studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at the age of 26 will no longer start smoking with 99% probability, even after that.
"You can see from children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a minor impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws favored the black market, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the roads of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago at the Australian Supreme Court with their legal challenge.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
It's a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media is precisely the population to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banished tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most traders to stop putting cigarettes into stores. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"Anyone who markets tobacco and has only a small area left to advertise their products will not be able to get around the Internet," says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media, such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in experiences with brands written by "normal people."
You have to ask yourself the question: is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of focusing on marketing, industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organisation about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries are trading more heavily with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has had talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harder laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I'm just ignoring her.
"You just take a smoke and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo printed with a mouth tumor.
Frankly, there's only one reason I'd quit, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says that uniform packaging has made it difficult to refill its shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four," Yu says.
"The government should have banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said to ourselves okay, that's it, we're shutting down," he adds visibly angry.
