So I had enough time to worry about getting bored.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting for half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it's okay for us - and our children - to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting ways of thinking, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us today are staring almost constantly at one or the other screen, we no longer benefit from the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't think so.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The house walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience "of wanting to do a satisfactory job, but not being able to do so".
Boredom therefore differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In the case of apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in "disturbing the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly."
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're boring, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - on German, for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom in the Aspects of Attention", published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
Those who heard the barely audible television said that they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could not find a reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or exhausting task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous job - "like the search for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that rambling and scribbling, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a booming speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed in the 1980s a "Scala to Boredom susceptibility".
On the scale there are statements like "Many things I have to do repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more often bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of Westflorida - especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Today, 21 years later, Professor Larson says that he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he was sure that "youth is felt to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily routine.
Back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take extreme physical risks and succumb to gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. Professor Vodanovich has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With the boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do right now.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you'll be happy.
But television can provide happiness in the short term, but they disappear in the long run.
So if you're enough for your bored child to have an iPad, you can get it away from boredom. However, it didn't teach you how to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers from one situation to the other."
The child not only learns to talk, but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel at home away from constant activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we often have to be bored, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that the truth is that people are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment in which we are constantly being overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with the noise once the noise has stopped."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
The 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco stands for an offense in the south-east of Colorado, which will soon be legal in this state: the possession of a few marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
