As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are traded as national standard cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at federal level as a crime.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several sensational arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely permitted the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former Obama administration drug policy advisor, believes that while criminal officials are unlikely to enter doors to confiscate small amounts of drugs, they are likely to refuse to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana businesses under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local community administrations approved moratoria for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, adopted a six-month ban, which is expected to be passed next week.
