The cause of dying for AIDS today is a late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the results of the investigation: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried "to weaken" without any apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such dedication that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already done harm and exhausted their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who receives treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of HCG's HIV unit, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the start of treatment, and that those who are not drug addicts have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above remarks mean that those who receive the diagnosis HIV-positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "become 75 years of age without problems as long as they are under control," this expert explained.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA Annual Report), it is still true that 60 percent of patients in the national database have died since AIDS appeared.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by the month of May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
- So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have had no drug supply problems. The problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they don't know their state of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why all persons who require this must be offered massive detection tests."
This proposal is agreed by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also by the patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, for the sole reason that he had been made a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I prefer to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I feed well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the worldwide AIDS day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken care of the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
At the designated places "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; previously they were delivered individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Adolescents are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need it for?" is a widespread mockery of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health care system, which young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in delivery equipment in public toilets of facilities frequented by young people.
It is not intended to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether there would be a distribution of reserves under his administration.
"Sexuality doesn't look like this; it's best to bring the condoms closer to those already engaged in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state is fourth in new and cumulative cases of AIDS, and 13th in relation to HIV.
92% of contagion occurs via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for each registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a judgment that does not recognise the restructuring of the Vitro Group's liabilities achieved through a trade dispute in Mexico, a disastrous precedent will be created for any national company with branches in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
So it could be said that the procedures for the survival of companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the land of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the verdict given on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas court for the northern district of Texas results in Mexican companies being helplessly exposed to seizure of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court for three inconsistencies.
While the judge points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the court of appeal of the Fifth Circuit, based in New Orleans, first of all says that the main proceedings are the trade dispute dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings for companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
Indeed, to this end, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created, using the American Law Institute as a mediator.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the votes of the companies, the majority required for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved after recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy assets held by Vitro’s branches with their parent company.
However, this possibility is recognised by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities were confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Bundesinstitut für Handelskonkurs) among the Group's companies.
It is also true that after the votes of the branches were withdrawn, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who complained to the courts of the United States against Vitro, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have achieved a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards in the context of the major economic crisis in the United States, which struck the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family objected to the same court of appeal so that the vote would be taken in plenary, i.e. by all judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not accepted, the Cerciorare appeal is filed, which calls for the review of the proceedings by a higher court, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court left aside a document sent by the government of Mexico under the Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court), describing the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Law on Commercial Concourses, and pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It is also noted that the country has been subject to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules on cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
